04411nam a22005055i 9780822390893DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223908937 a10.1515/97808223908932doi  a(DE-B1597)553559  a(OCoLC)1181631796  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0440002bisacsh1 aParedez, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSelenidad :bSelena, Latinos, and the Performance of Memory /cDeborah Paredez. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (284 p.) :b40 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Selenidad and Latinidad in the 1990s -- tOne. Soundtracks of Selenidad: "Disco Medley" and "Como la Flor" -- tTwo. Colonial Past, Tejano Present: Civic Maintenance at Selena's Memorial -- tThree. Selena Forever, Latino Futures -- tFour. Becoming Selena, Becoming Latina -- tFive. "Como la Flor" Reprised: Queer Selenidad -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn outpouring of memorial tributes and public expressions of grief followed the death of the Tejana recording artist Selena Quintanilla Pérez in 1995. The Latina superstar was remembered and mourned in documentaries, magazines, websites, monuments, biographies, murals, look-alike contests, musicals, drag shows, and more. Deborah Paredez explores the significance and broader meanings of this posthumous celebration of Selena, which she labels "Selenidad." She considers the performer's career and emergence as an icon within the political and cultural transformations in the United States during the 1990s, a decade that witnessed a "Latin explosion" in culture and commerce alongside a resurgence of anti-immigrant discourse and policy.Paredez argues that Selena's death galvanized Latina/o efforts to publicly mourn collective tragedies (such as the murders of young women along the U.S.-Mexico border) and to envision a brighter future. At the same time, reactions to the star's death catalyzed political jockeying for the Latino vote and corporate attempts to corner the Latino market. Foregrounding the role of performance in the politics of remembering, Paredez unravels the cultural, political, and economic dynamics at work in specific commemorations of Selena. She analyzes Selena's final concert, the controversy surrounding the memorial erected in the star's hometown of Corpus Christi, and the political climate that served as the backdrop to the touring musicals Selena Forever and Selena: A Musical Celebration of Life. Paredez considers what "becoming" Selena meant to the young Latinas who auditioned for the biopic Selena, released in 1997, and she surveys a range of Latina/o queer engagements with Selena, including Latina lesbian readings of the star's death scene and queer Selena drag. Selenidad is a provocative exploration of how commemorations of Selena reflected and changed Latinidad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390893zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390893.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles